Utility programs
****************

   The following utility programs are included in the MiamiSSL archive
and installed in the "Miami:" directory during the installation of
MiamiSSL.


 @{" MiamiSSLCiphers " Link "NODE_MIAMISSLCIPHERS"}                             MiamiSSLCiphers
 @{" MiamiSSLClient " Link "NODE_MIAMISSLCLIENT"}                              MiamiSSLClient
 @{" MiamiSSLIDEA " Link "NODE_MIAMISSLIDEA"}                                MiamiSSLIDEA
 @{" MiamiSSLUSAArcFour " Link "NODE_MIAMISSLUSAARCFOUR"}                          MiamiSSLUSAArcFour
 @{" MiamiSSLVersion " Link "NODE_MIAMISSLVERSION"}                             MiamiSSLVersion


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_MIAMISSLCIPHERS" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_MIAMISSLCIPHERS"
@Next "NODE_MIAMISSLCLIENT"
@Toc "NODE_UTILITY"

MiamiSSLCiphers
===============

   MiamiSSLCiphers displays all ciphers available with the current
setup of MiamiSSL. Available options:

@{b}-v@{ub}
     Verbose output. Display detailed cipher explanation instead of
     brief, ':'-separated list of ciphers.

@{b}-ssl2@{ub}
     Display only ciphers available in SSLv2 mode.

@{b}-ssl3@{ub}
     Display only ciphers available in SSLv3 mode.


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_MIAMISSLCLIENT" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_MIAMISSLCLIENT"
@Next "NODE_MIAMISSLIDEA"
@Prev "NODE_MIAMISSLCIPHERS"
@Toc "NODE_UTILITY"

MiamiSSLClient
==============

   MiamiSSLClient is a utility that allows you to establish connections
to SSL servers (e.g. secure web servers), and monitor the connection
establishment phase and all session parameters, e.g. encryption
strength, certificates, ciphers, SSL versions etc.

   MiamiSSLClient first establishes a connection and displays all
related parameters, and then quits.

   Available options:

@{b}-host (hostname)@{ub}
     Host to connect to. The default is "localhost".

@{b}-port (portnumber)@{ub}
     Port number to connect to. The default is 443 (https).

@{b}-connect (host:port)@{ub}
     Combination of "-host" and "-port" options

@{b}-verify (depth)@{ub}
     Enables peer certificate verification and sets the maximum depth
     of certificate chains.

@{b}-cert (filename)@{ub}
     Filename of client side certificate. PEM format assumed.

@{b}-key (filename)@{ub}
     Filename of private key for client side certificate. Only
     necessary if the client side certificate does not already contain
     the private key. PEM format assumed.

@{b}-CApath (pathname)@{ub}
     Pathname of certificate repository. PEM format assumed.

@{b}-CAfile (filename)@{ub}
     Filename of certificate repository. PEM format assumed.

@{b}-reconnect@{ub}
     Try to disconnect and reconnect five times with the same session
     ID. For debugging purposes. Does not work with all servers.

@{b}-showcerts@{ub}
     Show all certificates in the chain.

@{b}-debug@{ub}
     Show additional debugging information, such as packet hex dumps.

@{b}-state@{ub}
     Show all internal SSL states.

@{b}-quiet@{ub}
     Suppress most output.

@{b}-ssl2/-ssl3/-tls1@{ub}
     Only use the specified SSL/TLS version.

@{b}-no_tls1/-no_ssl2/-no_ssl3@{ub}
     Reject negotiation of the specified SSL/TLS version.

@{b}-bugs@{ub}
     Enable all workarounds for bugs in SSL servers. Try this option if
     you get an error message otherwise.

@{b}-cipher@{ub}
     Specify the cipher to use, e.g. "DES-CBC3-MD5".


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_MIAMISSLIDEA" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_MIAMISSLIDEA"
@Next "NODE_MIAMISSLUSAARCFOUR"
@Prev "NODE_MIAMISSLCLIENT"
@Toc "NODE_UTILITY"

MiamiSSLIDEA
============

   @{i}Before using this program please read the important background
information in @{"Enabling IDEA" Link "NODE_ENABLEIDEA"}.@{ui}

   MiamiSSLIDEA enables or disables the IDEA cipher in the currently
installed MiamiSSL encryption library. The program patches the
encryption library, i.e. the change is permanent and does not have to be
repeated after rebooting. However each time you upgrade MiamiSSL to a
new version IDEA is automatically disabled again.

   To enable or disable the IDEA cipher just run MiamiSSLIDEA in a
shell window and follow the dialog.


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_MIAMISSLUSAARCFOUR" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_MIAMISSLUSAARCFOUR"
@Next "NODE_MIAMISSLVERSION"
@Prev "NODE_MIAMISSLIDEA"
@Toc "NODE_UTILITY"

MiamiSSLUSAArcFour
==================

   @{i}Before using this program please read the important background
information in @{"Enabling ARCFOUR" Link "NODE_ENABLEARCFOUR"}.@{ui}

   MiamiSSLArcFour enables or disables the ARCFOUR cipher in the US
version of the MiamiSSL encryption library, if it is currently
installed. If you are using the international version of the MiamiSSL
encryption library then this program has no use for you.

   The program patches the encryption library, i.e. the change is
permanent and does not have to be repeated after rebooting.  However
each time you upgrade MiamiSSL to a new version ARCFOUR is
automatically disabled again.

   To enable or disable the ARCFOUR cipher just run MiamiSSLUSAArcFour
in a shell window and follow the dialog.


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_MIAMISSLVERSION" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_MIAMISSLVERSION"
@Prev "NODE_MIAMISSLUSAARCFOUR"
@Toc "NODE_UTILITY"

MiamiSSLVersion
===============

   MiamiSSLVersion displays version information about the currently
installed version of MiamiSSL. Available options:

@{b}-v@{ub}
     Display version information (default).

@{b}-b@{ub}
     Display build date.

@{b}-o@{ub}
     Display build options (currently no effect).

@{b}-f@{ub}
     Display build flags (currently no effect).

@{b}-a@{ub}
     Display all of the above.


@EndNode

@Node "NODE_HISTORY" "MiamiSSL.guide/NODE_HISTORY"
@Next "NODE_SUPPORT"
@Prev "NODE_UTILITY"
@Toc "Main"

History
*******

@{b}2.21@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Removed DSA algorithm from default configuration because it
          is too slow on most Amigas. Added environment variable
          ENV:MIAMI/SSLENABLEDSA to enable it on demand.

        @{b}*@{ub} Removed some expired certificates and added a few new ones.

@{b}2.14@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Minor API addition to make SRP support in MiamiTelnet more
          efficient.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added CAST-128 encryption algorithm. It cannot be used by SSL
          or SSH yet, but is supported by SRP-negotiated telnet
          encryption in MiamiTelnet.

        @{b}*@{ub} Updated to latest OpenSSL 0.9.3 snapshot.

@{b}2.11@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Bug fix: "MiamiSSLCiphers ?" would busy-loop.

        @{b}*@{ub} Bug fix: Certificate verification did not work, because the
          hash function changed from SSLeay to OpenSSL, and MiamiSSL 2.0
          still used the old codes. New certificates are now installed
          in "Miami:SSL/v2certs".

        @{b}*@{ub} Updated to latest OpenSSL 0.9.3 snapshot.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added ARCTWO cipher back into US version.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added option to enable ARCFOUR cipher in the US version.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added option to enable IDEA cipher in all versions.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added utility programs MiamiSSLUSAArcFour, MiamiSSLIDEA and
          MiamiSSLClient.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added AmigaGuide documentation.

        @{b}*@{ub} Improved version negotiation fallback to also allow fallbacks
          to SSLv3 for compatibility with a wider range of non-compliant
          servers.

@{b}2.0@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Migrated sources to OpenSSL 0.9.3 snapshot.

        @{b}*@{ub} Added support for SSLv2 and SSLv3

@{b}1.5@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Added BLOWFISH cipher for MiamiSecureShell.

@{b}1.4@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Extended API to support functions needed by MiamiSecureShell.

@{b}1.3@{ub}
     Minor changes only.

@{b}1.2@{ub}
        @{b}*@{ub} Extended API to support functions needed for MS-CHAP.

@{b}1.1@{ub}
     Minor changes only.

@{b}1.0@{ub}
     Initial release.


@EndNode

